\begin_layout Section
Synthetic Data-set Creation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Goal
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generate 2-classes data with 20 features each.
 Each class is given by a multivariate Gaussian distribution.
 Covariance matrix should not be spherical in nature.
 Generate 2000 samples for each class and make sure there exists some overlap
 within the classes.
 Partition them into train set and test set by randomly picking 70 % data
 of each class ( 1400 points each ) and the remaining 30 %.
 This dataset is referred to as DS1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need to generate 2 different Gaussian distributions with a random centroid
 and they should sufficiently overlap.
 Also, the covariance matrix needs to be positive definite.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a randomly generated matrix of order 
\begin_inset Formula $pxp$
\end_inset

.
 Now the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 generated from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 as follows will be positive definite.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $B=pI+\frac{1}{2}(A+A^{T})$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Thus, generating the covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 like this, we can make sure that it is not spherical and positive definite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the 2 distributions are generated and are labelled as 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Performance reported on DS1 are on the test-set which accounts for 30 %
 of the generated data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Linear Classification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Goal
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To learn a linear classifier by using regression on an indicator variable.
 The accuracy, precision, recall and f-score on the train set are reported.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A linear classifier performs a regression on the data points 
\begin_inset Formula $(\,X\,)$
\end_inset

 and the labels 
\begin_inset Formula $(\,Y\,)$
\end_inset

.
 For a given 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon R^{p}$
\end_inset

 , say the label is 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Now, a linear regression on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 finds 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta,\beta_{0}\,\epsilon\,R^{p}$
\end_inset

 such that,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
y_{predicted}=\beta_{0}+x^{T} & \beta
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

subject to minimising,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sum||\,\,y_{predicted}-y\, & ||
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The solution can be analytically obtained and is found to be,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[\beta_{0},\beta]=(X^{T}X)^{-1}X^{T} & Y
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Classification is done by thresholding the 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{predicted}$
\end_inset

 for a given 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and then the appropriate class is predicted.
 For instance, here if 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{predicted}>0.5$
\end_inset

, Class-1 is predicted else Class-0 is predicted.
\end_layout

