\begin_layout Section
k-NN classifier
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Goal
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To use k-NN ( k Nearest Neighbours ) to build a classifier to classify the
 points in DS1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
k-NN is a classifier which models a function which is region-wise constant.
 Given a point, k-NN predicts the majority class in the neighbourhood formed
 by the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 nearest points from the trainset.
 As a result, it predicts the same class for a given region as the majority
 class remains the same in that neighbourhood.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Here, we have 2 classes, Class-0 and Class-1.
 Thus, it reduces to a binary classification problem.
 One important issue with k-NN is fixing the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 For a large 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, decision boundaries are smoother, whereas for small 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 it is rigid and hard.
 Usually, it is determined after experimenting with different values of
 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Here the different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 are considered ranging from 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

 and the performance is reported.
\end_layout

