\begin_layout Section
Data imputation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Goal
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are given the Communities and Crime dataset from UCI repository.
 Some of the data points have some of the attributes missing.
 Goal is to fix the data points and fill in the missing values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to fill in the missing values, we need to estimate the distribution
 of the attribute and extrapolate.
 Statistical measures like mean and median can be used to fill in the missing
 values.
 If the attribute is categorical or text, mode ( most frequent observation
 ) can be used to impute the missing values.
 Another approach is to learn a k-NN classifier on that attribute and predict
 the missing values.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Since the missing attribute is not categorical here, using mode is not suitable.
 We can't use k-NN as the attributes missing can not be assumed piecewise
 constant.
 Among mean and median, median seems to be a better choice as the values
 taken by the attribute are not uniformly distributed and are sort of discrete.
 Therefore it makes more sense, to impute the missing values using median.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The missing values were imputed using median of the given values and complete
 dataset is attached in the source.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Linear Regression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Goal
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal is to fit the above data using linear regression.
 Performance is analysed on the test data averaged over 5 different 80-20
 splits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A linear classifier performs a regression on the data points 
\begin_inset Formula $(\,X\,)$
\end_inset

 and the labels 
\begin_inset Formula $(\,Y\,)$
\end_inset

.
 For a given 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon R^{p}$
\end_inset

 , say the label is 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Now, a linear regression on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 finds 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta,\beta_{0}\,\epsilon\,R^{p}$
\end_inset

 such that,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
y_{predicted}=\beta_{0}+x^{T} & \beta
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

subject to minimising,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sum||\,\,y_{predicted}-y\, & ||
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The solution can be analytically obtained and is found to be,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[\beta_{0},\beta]=(X^{T}X)^{-1}X^{T} & Y
