\begin_layout Subsection
Approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes the input data tends to have correlated features and as a result
 some weights tend to go beyond limits ( to large values ) and nearly cancel
 out the contribution of these two features to the final prediction.
 To prevent such solution, we constrain the weights to have small values.
 Instead of having a hard threshold on the norm of weights, we can formulate
 it as an optimization problem as shown below.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
y_{predicted}=\beta_{0}+x^{T} & \beta
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

subject to minimising,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sum||\,\,y_{predicted}-y\, & ||+\lambda||\beta||
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is called the regularization parameter and other symbols have their usual
 meaning.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 captures the effect of high value of weights in the final solution.
 The solution can be analytically obtained and is found to be,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
