\begin_layout Section
Logistic Regression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Goal
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the given dataset ( called DS2 ) which consists of a number of images
 of different categories, we need to perform a 2-class logistic regression
 on it, by extracting features from it.
 Performance using both L1 and L2 penalty is analysed and reported.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Logistic regression is a regression model where the dependent variable is
 categorical.
 Using linear regression in such cases faces 2 problems: it might predict
 value outside the range of the values which the dependent variable can
 take, and also solutions get affected due to class imbalance.
 Logistic regression solves these problems by a different cost function
 which maximises likelihood.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

A logistic regressor performs a regression on the data points 
\begin_inset Formula $(\,X\,)$
\end_inset

 and the labels 
\begin_inset Formula $(\,Y\,)$
\end_inset

.
 For a given 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon R^{p}$
\end_inset

 , say the label is 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Now, logistic regression on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 finds 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta,\theta_{0}\,\epsilon\,R^{p}$
\end_inset

 such that,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
y_{predicted}=h_{\theta} & (x)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

where,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
h_{\theta} & (x)=\frac{1}{1+e^{-(\theta_{0}+x^{T}\theta)}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

and the cost function is minimised.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
cost,\,L(h_{\theta}(x),\,y)= & \begin{cases}
-log(h_{\theta}(x)) & if\,y=1\\
-log(1-h_{\theta}(x)) & if\,y=0
\end{cases}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

This cost function maximises likelihood and our prediction is by modelling
 a sigmoid of a linear fit.
\end_layout

